{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602061/1937111801/0151.xml":{"full_text":"Barkley Seen\nFoes of Revision May\nBe Cause of Row,\nWriter Holds.\nBy DAVID LAWRENCE.\nALTHOUGH there are a great\nmany things besides the repeal\nor revision of the undistributed\nsurplus tax which would be\nhelpful to economic recovery, senti\nment in Congress has crystallized\ncuriously enough on that one tax.\nr i uni hu\nthe country the\ndemand for\nchange in the tax\nlaw Is coming in\nto members of\nk Congress until\nthe undistributed\nsurplus tax con\ntroversy seems to\nsymbolize almost\nentirely whether\nthe administra-\ntion is acting in\ngood faith in its\nrecent assurances j\nto business.\nIt Is beinc rec\nognized here that the skepticism\nwhich, rightly or wrongly, exists out\nside of Washington about the meaning\nof the President's message to Congress\ncan be removed not by wards but by\naction.\nIf Congress, therefore, should in the\nnext few days do something about the\nundistributed surplus tax, it would\ncarry great weight with the business\nelements of the country. For it would\nbe a step that indicated the alertness\nof Congress to the business problems\nof the Nation and also the readiness\nof the President to make action square\nwith the promise he has just made to\nencourage private capital spending.\nj .Vtiimuf,! vi vwiikitas,\nThe psychology of Congress is be\nginning to be an important factor in\nthe restoration of confidence in the\nbusiness world. Up to now Congress\nhas been regarded as a rubber stamp\ninstitution which would okay the\nwildest -spending plans and all the\neconomic fallacies thal might emanate\nfrom the bram trust. Today, however,\nthe special session of Congress really\nis a godsend to business because an\nopportunity is afforded for prompt\naction toward a reversal of the policies\nthat have brought on the market\npanics of 1937,\nt To a certain extent, of course, the\npresent business recession is the result\nof unwarranted fears about the future,\nbut to an even larger extent the key\nto the future lies in stilling those\nfears and preventing new ones from\narising.\nWhether it is fear or not. or can\ncellation of orders due to diminished\ndemand, the facts about the increase 1\nin unemployment are impressive. Thus\nthe National Industrial Conference\nBoard has announced that a tele\ngraphic survey based on information\nreceived by wire from more than 1,200\ncompanies regularly reporting pay\nroll data to the board shows employ\nment to have been 989.669 in August\nof this year, 967.510 in October and\nnow it is down to 926,368 as of No\nvember 13.\nThis steady decline has been ac\ncomplished also by a considerable re- j\nduction in the hours of work due to\niay-ons. I\nSome of the radicals and so-called j\nliberals in Congress are. of course, un- j\nwilling to recognize that a business re-\ncession even exists. They gloss it over 1\nin their public statements, and they\nare getting ready to oppose tax revi\nsion and any of the other constructive j\nsteps that might be urged to help\neconomic recovery.\nAttitude of One Faction.\nSome of these elements are truly\nsocialistic at heart and have no inter\nest in preserving the system of private\ninitiative or private capital, and would\njust as soon see chaos as recovery be\ncause it would open up opportunities\nfor more Government control and reg\nulation as well as Government owner\nship. These men are sincere in their\nbeliefs and are conscientiously of the\nopinion that America would be better\noff with public ownership of most\nbusinesses and industries than under\nprivate ownership.\nBut the wing of the President\u2019s ad\nvisers that believes in such things is\nnot at the moment as favorably re\nceived as the economic advisers who\nare counseling that everything be done\nconsistent with fairness and equity to\nencourage the functioning of the pri\nvate capital system. There is a trend\ntoward constructive solutions more in\nline with what orthodox economists\nhave recommended.\nIn Congress some of the Democratic\nleaders are saying they cannot get the\nrevision of the undistributed surplus\ntax through even though there is a\nsubstantial number of both houses ac\nknowledged to be in favor of the\nchange. Perhaps some more data on\nthe business recession will have to\ncome out before some of the politically\nminded, who still are clinging to the\nillusions of 1936 and the \"everything\nis rosy\u201d idea of last summer, will bow\nWhat\u2019s Back of It All\nWashington Hears Rumors of War in the Pacific as\nBuild-up for \"Plebiscite\u201d Bills.\nBy H. R. BAUKHACE.\nIF A fairly healthy \u201cwar scare\u201d doesn't break by the time this reaches\ntype, cue is due shortly.#\nIt has been rumbling around in strange corners of Washington\nfor ;>4 hours preeeding the time of this writing. The war will be,\naccording to the ramblers, in thr Pacific, of course, and it is billed for a\nJune I opening except in case of rain.\nThere is something back of all this smoke, but it isn\u2019t gunfire. At\nleast caissons haven't started rolling as yet.\nHowever, there are a couple of red-hot \u201cplcbiscite-on-war\"\nbills in Congress. A number of veterans\u2019 organizations have passed\nresolutions against any war except in case of invasion of North or\nCentral America. Some of these have, and others shortly will, back\none or another of the \u201cplebiscite\u201d bills, which make a vote of the\nwhole people mandatory before u'ar can be declared, except in\ncase of invasion.\nThat may be one reason for the war talk. The best time to sell insur\nance is when it looks as if there is likely to be a fire.\nAnother reason for war talk is the continued rumor that a big arma\nment program is in the wind It can now be definitely stated that such a\nprogram is favorably considered bv the White House and will certainly be\nbrought forth as a measure for stimulating private industry if other means\nfail\u2014perhaps, in any case, In the name of absolutely essential national\nucrvnse.\n\nThe aviation industry\u2014or a representative portion of it\u2014took the\nreport of the Maritime Commission on \"aircraft and the merchant marine\"\non the chin.\nWhat they feared, as suggested in this column last month, came true.\nThe Maritime Commission approached them, bearing gifts.\nUnless the flying weather changes between now and then, this is\nabout what representative spokesmen of the industry will say:\n\"We don't need a subsidy. New lines may. Let them take it, but\nwe're afraid of getting governmental red tape into the feed lines.\n\"Foreign competition doesn't bother us because, while there may\nstill be a 'freedom of the seas.\u2019 there isn't much 'freedom of the\nair: Ann ship under a foreign flag can steam into New York harbor.\n\"This is not true of planes. Only foreign nations which permit\nour planes to lend on their shores receive reciprocal rights here.\nBut foreign nations (even sister democracies) aren't crazy about\nhaving any foreigners flying nigh, wide and handsome over their territory\nwhich every now and then contains a few secret fortifications as well as\nbabbling brooks, landing fields, meadows and pastures green.\"\nfact that they don\u2019t want to be\nput under the commission, or the\nDepartment of Commerce or the\nPast Office or anywhere but the\nInterstate Commerce Commission,\nthat the airplane people report low\nvisibility when they look for the\nmerits of the report.\nMr. Kennedy himself says,\n\u201cIt. seems fairly evident that the\nvolume of nassencer. mail and ex\npress traffic available to aircraft is ample in the trans-Atlantic field, for\nexample, to create income necessary to eventual profitable operation\" and\nthat large subsidies wouldn't be required, except on other routes \"where\nthe traffic is lighter.\u2019\u2019\n\n\"The Pope-McGill Farm Bill will be the base of the measure the\ncommittee will draw up,\" naid Senator \"Cotton Ed\" Smith, back from\nDixie with a touch of fire in his eye, \"but when we finally get through\nwith it the authors will hardly recognize it.\"\nThat is a fair sample of the way the present session is ready to go\nabout the work it was hailed back from home to do.\nSenator Smith is against all compulsoiy control; thinks the Supreme\nCourt won't swallow it and complains that Secretai*y Wallace has hung\ntoo many restrictions on the cotton loans.\nBut don't think that \u201cCotton Ed\u2019\u2019 is entirely destructive He has\na brand new, red-hot contribution to offer for the consideration of\ngoi'ernmental cotton experts. He thinks their present data on the\nworld supply of cotton are unreliable and the means of collecting\nthem is inadequate. In short, he thinks there ought to be a law,\nand he's going to introduce one.\nSenator Smith's bill would create a commission authorized to visit\nall foreign countries in which cotton is produced or consumed. The com\nexperts, take all the time needed\nto get the facts, presumably evi?n\nlonger than it will take to get a cot\ncon control bill through Congress.\n\nThere may be a lot of legisla\ntion neglected at the present ses\nsion which will eventually get by.\nBut one bill that had plenty of\nsteam behind it once is probably\n6iucurtLK**u lurevcr. inis rnpasurp\nmay not have meant much to you, but a lot would have been said about\nhigher living cost if it had not been dropped\nIt's the famous 70-car\u201d bill, and the story *behind its demise is short 1\nand interesting.\nThis measure, you recall, was sponsored by Senator McCarran and\nproposed to limit freight trains to 70 cars. It was supposed to be a safety\nmeasure. It caused a loud wail on the part of the railroads.\nNow it appears that labor isn't as interested in \u201csafety\u201d as it\nis in what goes into the pay envelope.\nAt least, when the railroads, after the long-drawn-out arbitration in\nChicago, finally agreed to an increase in the base pay of the men, the\nrailroad brotherhoods agreed that they would let the \"70-car bill\u201d rest,\nif not rust, on the\u2019rails.\n(Copyright. 1937.)\nto the facts and begin to realize that\nunless Congress acts promptly the re\ncovery swing will be postponed be\nyond the November, 1938, elections.\nRepublican Position.\nFrom a Republican point of view,\ninaction may bp good political wish\nfulness, but the Nation should not be\nrun from any political point of view\nat the moment of an economic crisis.\nThe Republicans, therefore, are ag\ngressive in demanding change, but\nthey are aware that the Democratic\nleadership is stubbornly resisting it,\nespecially in the Senate. It's a tough\nspot for Majority Leader Barkley, but\nunless he gets his followers in step\nwith the times he will have an insur\ngency on his hands, with Chairman\nPat Harrison of the Senate Finance\nCommittee probably leading the bat\ntle. And that would not help the\npolitical situation inside the Demo\ncratic party very much in a session\njust prior to congressional elections.\n(Copyright, 1937.)\n\nArgentina Prospers.\nProduction, earnings and employ\nment are near new high levels In\nArgentina.\nX! X -IX ij XlkJI7A X VJ\nI\nrJ'HE opinions of the writers on this page are their own, not\nnecessarily The Star\u2019s. Such opinions are presented in\nThe Star\u2019s effort to give all sides of questions of interest to its\nreaders, although such opinions may be contradictory among\nthemselves and directly opposed to The Star\u2019s.\nA Misunderstood Bill\nPopular. Misconceptions Exist Regarding \"Anti\nLynching\u201d Measure, Writer Declares.\nBy MARK SULLIVAN.\nIF ETERNAL vigilance is the price\nof liberty, so is eternal clarity the\nprice of understanding. And so\nalso is understanding the path to\nwise action. All three of these truisms\nare applicable to the so-called anti\nlynching\" bill now before Congress.\nLack of understanding of the bill is\nwidespread, is indeed almost univer\nsal. The very\nname by which\nthe bill is popu\nlarly called is\nmisleading. \u201cAn\nti-lynching'* is a\nconvenient\nphrase for writers\nof headlines\nstrugg ling for\ncond e n s a t i o n\na g a i nst limita\ntions of space.\nBut this is not an\n\u201canti lynching\"\nbill. The bill does\nnot make lynch\ning any more a\nunite limn it \u00abiv\\n_y.'> imn uo u. iut\nnew crime created by the bill is failure\nof sheriffs or other local officials, to\nbe duly diligent in preventing and\npunishing lynehings.\nThe popular misunderstanding of\nthe bill goes further. The American\nInstitute of Public Opinion recently\nconducted one of its \u201csampling\" polls\nto find out whether or not the so\ncalled anti-lynching bill is popular.\nThe institute discovered that 72 out of\nevery 100 persons queried favored the\nbill. But just what was the question\nwhich the institute put before those\nwhom it queried? The question read:\n\"Should Congress pass a law which\nwould make lynching a Federal\ncrime?\"\nBesides, how many of the persons\nquestioned really understood the bill?\nHow many of thpm were familiar with\njust what it would do, what effect it\nwould have on the American structure\nof government, on the distinction be\ntween State sovereignty and Federal\nsovereignty? The persons questioned\nby the institute must have included,\none assumes, a cross section of the\npopulation as a whole, from the least\ninformed to the best informed. If the\nquestionnaire did not reach all kinds\nof persons, the results of It would be\nby that fart misleading. But if the\nquestionnaire did include the less well\ninformed, its results must be based in\npart upon the answers of persons who\nhave little understanding of he meas\nure. Without lcnowing anything of\nthe process by which the Institute of\nPublic Opinion conducts its question\nnaires, I should imagine that a consid\nerable number of those who answered\n\u2022'yes\" were merely saying, in effect,\nthat they believed lynching to be odi\nous.\nEffect of Measure.\nActually, what the bill does is to give\na new and portentous power to the\nFederal Government. It would au\nthorize the Federal Government to\nsend a Federal official into any county\nor city in which a lynching has\noccurred, to decide whether the local\nState or countv officials had practiced\nall diligent efforts'* in preventing or\npunishing the lynching. If the Fed\neral official felt the State or county\nofficials had not made \"all diligent\nefforts,\" then the Federal Government\nwould proceed to fine or imprison the\nState or county official and also to\nassess damages of from $2,500 to\n$10,000 against the county in which\nthe lynching occurred.\nThis immense extension of Fed\neral jurisdiction, this subjection of\nlocal government to government from\nWashington, is proposed at a fateful\ntime. It is proposed when those now\nin control of the Federal Government\nare engaged in an attempt, on many\nfronts and through many devices, to\nextend their power to a point at which,\nin the judgment of thoughtful persons,\nthe States would become little more\nthan mere obsolete names on the map.\nThere is another path to under\nstanding of the \"anti-lynching\u201d bill,\nthe political path. From the Civil\nWar on there has been a considerable\nNegro population in such cities as\nCincinnati, Indianapolis and St. Louis.\nFor nearly 70 years these colored per\nsons voted the Republican ticket.\nSince the three cities were in pivotal\nStates, States more or less evenly\ndivided between Republicans and\nDemocrats, this vote was extremely\nimportant to the Republicans. It has\nbeen said, and J suspect statistics\nmight bear it out, that if every colored\nperson in Ohio, Indiana and Missouri\nhad always voted the Democratic\nticket, the Republicans would have\nlost those States in many presidential\nelections and consequently lost the\npresidential elections.\n\nGathered in Large Cities.\nAfter the Great War considerable\nNegro populations gathered in other\nNorthern cities\u2014New York, D-\u2019troit,\nChicago. Here again, until 1933. these\ngroups commonly voted Republican.\nSo long as the colored persons voted\nRepublican, the Republican party\ncultivated them by proposing in Con\ngress measures favorable to the Negroes\neverywhere. I do not recall whether\nthe Republicans proposed anti-lynch\ning bills like the present one. But the\nRepublicans frequently proposed a\nmeasure which would have meant a\nsimilar invasion of States\u2019 rights by\nme federal Government. The Re\npublicans frequently proposed a so\ncalled \u201cforce\u201d bill under whirh Federal\nofficials and Federal soldiers would\nhave been present at the polls in\nSouthern States to exercise coercion\nupon State and county officials con\nducting the local elections.\nSince 1932 the Negro colonies in\nNorthern cities have prevailingly voted\nDemocratic. So now it is the Demo\ncrats who father anti-lynching bills.\nThe one passed by the House early this\nyear was sponsored by a Democrat\nfrom New York City. Representative\nGavagan. The present bill in the\nSenate is fathered by a Democratic\nSenator from New York. Mr. Wagner,\nand a Democratic Senator from Indi\nana, Mr. Van Nuys. An anti-lynching\nbill that was before the Senate some\nfour years ago was fathered by a Dem\nocratic Senator from Colorado, Mr.\nCostigan.\nIn the present Congress both Re\npublicans and Democrats from the\nNorth will compete in their eagerness\nto support the anti-lynching bill\u2014the\nDemocrats because they have the Negro\nvote and hope to keep it, the Re\npublicans because they hope to get it\nback. But there is one Republican\nSenator who will not support the\nmeasure\u2014and he is perhaps the Sena\ntor most competent to have under\nstanding of its constitutional evil, its\nmenace to the American form of\ngovernment. Senator Borah has con\nV JiiVlOJjXV J.O, 1301.\nWe, fhe People\nWhether We Can Go From \"Here\u201d to \"There\u201d Under\nFlexible Constitution Seen Question Before U. S.\nBy JAY FRANKLIN.\nTHE special session of Congress illustrates Roosevelt\u2019s major contri\nbution to our public life: the re-establishment of representative\ngovernment as the focus of politics in American democracy.\nFive\u2014even four and three\u2014years ago, the system of checks\nand balances embodied in the old Constitution had taker, a form which\npalsied political action. The Executive was exalted\u2014at least until he began\nto propose measures which touched the fundamentals of the power of the\n\u201cecpnomic royalists.\u201d\nAt that time, of course, there was an outcry against \u201cdictatorship\u201d and\n\u201crubber-stamp\u201d Congress. Too large a measure of substantial sovereignty\nhad been farmed out to the judicial\noligarchy which operated the Fed\neral courts as a hand-maiden of\nbig business. The people were al\nlowed to vote for New Deal Repre\nsentatives and Senators in the\nsecure belief that their votes could\nbe nullified by the instrumentalities\nof conservative control.\n\nLast winter, spring and sum\nlvt v a n Ai i \u00bb\u00ab*f r-a ti* L f V. I O 4 4 a\npolicy in a stalemate which prevented the enactment of necessary reforms\nfor a period of over a yeaj\\ The proposal to reorganize the Supreme Court\nforced the big business interests back into the political arena in self-defense,\nbut not before the court had made major concessions in interpreting the\nelection returns. Congress ceased to be a \u2018\u2018rubber stamp.\u201d but at the price\nof blocking all but routine legislation. The President was compelled to re\nstate his objectives and narrow down his policies, to the central issue of\ncombating the great economic monopolies which dominate our national life\nand curtail individual enterprise and opportunity.\nNow all the lines come together. The business depression has brought\nthe Tory pack in full cry for reduced taxes on the big incomes and largo*\nbusinesses. They were cleverly, if somewhat unscrupulously, led into the\ndead-end street of a Congress in which the Wall Street demand for special\nfavors to speculators and multimillionaires is only one of a large number of\nurgent requests. The wages and hours bill for the benefit of industrial labor\nis another matter in which the proponents of legislative action are being\nreferred to the representatives of the neonle. Bumner crons of cntinn mm\nand wheat have produced a powerful demand for crop-control measures and\nanother triple-A program. The unemployment census is banking up the\nstatistics of the one-third of our people who are \"ill-housed, ill-clad, ill\nnourished,\u2019\u2019 in a powerful reminder that \"nobody must starve,\u201d that relipf\nmast be prompt and adequate and that budget balancing is possible only if\nthe \"human budget\u201d is first adjasted.\nSo the Tories, the organized workers, the farmers and the\nunemployed are once more brought face-to-face with their mutual\nproblems. There is nothing up Mr. Roosevelt\u2019s sleeve in this trans\naction, there are no white rabbits.\n\nAnd all the time the battle against the private utilities\u2014which most\nNew Dealers consider the crucial point, the \u201cbloody angle\u201d of the New Dpal\ngoes thundering ahead. A three-man court\u2014two-thirds of which is com\nDOSPCi of Npw Dpal Inrtp\u2019ps\u2014ic _\nhearing the request of the utilities\nfor an Injunction against T V. A.\nThe public utilities holding com\npany act is coming up. and the\naddition of Justice Black to the\nSupieme Court offers some assur\nance that the principle of business\nregulation involved will be sus\ntained. Direct pleadings before the\nSupreme Court have challenged\nthe old rule of \"replacement value\u201d\nas a raie oasis ior puonc utilities and nave proposed instead the old common\nlaw principle of \"prudent investment.\u201d\nWhile Congress is wrestling with Its legislative assignment, this power\nfight will continue and is expected to result in a judicial victory for New\nDeal legislation. At the first break, the \"seven T. V. A.'s\u201d measure will be\nfed into the hopper and with an election coming on it is believed that manv\nRepresentatives and Senators who were feeling their corporation oats last\nsummer will be disposed to \"go along with the administration,\u201d especially\nsince Mr. Roosevelt's popularity is undiminished.\nThis is the logical result of using representative institutions as th\u201d\nfocus of Democratic politics. It is an important contribution to the preser\nvation of American self-government. The question before the country now\n\u2014as it was last spring\u2014is whether our representative institutions will work,\nwhether our National Legislature will legislate, whether conservative con\ntrols in the courts and the Senate have been modified, and whether we can\ngo from ''here'' to \"there\" under the flexible Constitution.\n(CopyriKht. 1P3T.)\nA\u201413\nAn American\nYou Should\nKnow\nHead of Security Board\nHas Old Interest in\nLabor Laws.\nBY DELIA PYNCHON.\nIN RECENT times the United 8tates\nhas become security conscious.\n\u2022'Forgotten\u201d men, women and\nchildren are being remembered\nincreasingly in our national planning.\nArthur J. Altmeyer heads one of\nthe most ambitious of these new\nagencies as chairman of the Social\nSecurity Board. He personifies a life\ntime interest in the administration of\nlabor laws as a native of the labor\nconscious State of Wisconsin, where\nhe learned his labor philosophy from\nthe famous John R. Commons, dean\nof labor legislation. He epitomizes\nsocial security.\nwhich he calls a\n\"coined term,\u201d\n(calling them in\nsurance. welfare\nand relief \"ap\nproaches In the\nbroadest sense he\nfeels that the\nmany approaches\nof taxation, con\ntrol of monpy\nand banking.\n(housing, farm\ntenancy, conser\nvation of natural\nresources, labor\nlegislation, all are\nMr. Altmf> er.\nj 11\nu i art. uillV\nIn its narrowest sense the board i.s\nadministering the art itself, which is\nreally a bundle of 10 acts. The two\nmast important are the Federal old\nage benefits, administered entirely by\nthe Federal Government, and the\nunemployment compensation, admin\nistered along with the other eight, by\nState-Federal co-operation. Mr. Alt\nmeyer dubs them both \"insurance ap\nproaches\u201d to social security. Be\nginning with 1942 a retirement in\ncome based on earnings will be meted\nout to those over 65. This is a \"basic\nminimum security that the Govern\nment promotes.\u201d Mr. Altmeyer be\nlieves. It is not enough to take away\ninitiative or mollycoddle the public.\nMuch has been said of the 1 per cent\ntax on the lower group of wage\nearners. He explains that by re\nmarking that \"you cannot distort the\nprinciple Involved because of the\ninequalities in the wage structure\nreamer snouin a noor op put under\nwages by minimum-wage legislation.\nIn the \"relief and welfare approach\"\ngroup Mr. Altmeyer lists about 2.000,\n000 needy aged and blind and de\npendent children who have received\nmore than S500.000.000 combined\nState and Federal aid to date.\nMr. Altmeyer is as mentally keen\nas his fare denotes.\nBorn in De Pptp. Wis in 1891. with\nthree degrees from the University of\nWisconsin. Mr. Altmeyer became suc\ncessively a statistician for the Wis\nconsin Tax Commission, secretary of\nj the Wisconsin Industrial Commission.\nchief of the Compliance Division,\nN. R A Second Assistant Secretary\nof Labor, chairman of the Technical\nBoard appoint \u00abd by the President's\nCommittee on Economic Security. The\nj data so assembled was the basis of\nthe present Social Security Act.\nI sistently opposed anti-lynching bills\nand courageously met the criticism\nI visited upon him. Senator Borah does\n1 not condone lynching. But Senator\nBorah knows the danger of approach\ning the problem of lynching in this\nway.\n{Copyright. 1937.)\nDavid Lawrence.\nDEBUNKING DUNKING\nWO. 20 BY WILKINS COFFEE TEA\n\"THE FRANTIC RETRIEVE DUNK\"\nAn extra thrill for users of\n\ni Wilkins Coffee. We simply offer\nmore for the money, that's all!\nk, II\nftwanksN\nWE DON'T\n\\Nfc\u00a3Dir\nITALIAN\n(SWEET)\nAlcohol 15.6%\nby volume\nFRENCH\n(DRY)\nAlcohol 18%\nby volumo\nMark Sullivan.\nV^flPr% a'\nall enjoy\nCINZANO\nAll kinds of people in all kinds of coun\ntries enjoy Cinzano. Because Cinzano\ngoes everywhere is enjoyed by\neveryone who ever tried it in cocktails\nor as an aperitif. You'll like CINZANO.\ncinJano\nVERMOUTH\nCANADA DRY RINGER ALE, INC., N. Y.j SOLE DISTRIBUTOR\nr\ngBHj*A^JjgJ^Kj aftifl 14H 1 ^g \u201dJ| SB 3k IS ,*C| &|jgfe i 11fl <3 I|||k ji \u00a7Sjfgj&^J&|| yljp\nI\n\nIS YOUR LIVING ROOM READY\nJOR THE HOLIDAY SEASON?\nANOTHER J\nKROEHLER\nVALUE\nam\nWk\nI SPECIAL! 12-PIECE OUTFIT\nTwelve pieces, especially as\nsembled, to give you a Living\nRoom of charm and comfort.\nComprised of Kroehler-made\nSofa and Lounge Chair covered\nin durable tapestry, smart Oc\ncasional Chair, two End Tables, J\ntwo Sofa Pillows, Coffee Table, j\nLeatherette Hassock, and a I\nmatching Floor Lamp, Table I\nLamp and Bridge Lamp. 1\nUjn.MIL\nA 'Jur'nitur\u2019e\n7th E Sts. S. W. 8th Po. Ave. S. E.\n\nAV r\ni\n24 MONTHS\nTO PAY\nv NO INTEREST OR\nV CARRYING\nV CHARGES\n7","height":"31224","width":"22368"}}
